ral life; then to son John. Wethersfield property to son Samuel. Grandchildren John Russell (£20), John Talcott, Samuel Talcott, Elizabeth Talcott (£5 each). £5 to Rev. Samuel Stone; £5 toward a Latin school at Hartford. Overseers: Richard Lord Sr. and son John.","gift_to_stone":"Five pounds to 'my reverend and beloved teacher, Mr. Stone' — Rev. Samuel Stone, Hartford minister and colleague of Thomas Hooker"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"X00007","display_label":"Tobie Willet was a fellow passenger on the Lion in.","link_text":"Capt. Thomas Willet"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"I00006","display_label":"Tobie Willet was a fellow passenger on the Lion in.","link_text":"Mary Willet Buckingham"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00007","display_label":"Tobie Willet was a fellow passenger on the Lion in.","link_text":"Rev. Samuel Hooker"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"H00001","display_label":"co-founded Hartford with Talcott","link_text":"Rev. Thomas Hooker"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00090","display_label":"Both in the Adventurers Party 1635; both Hartford founders.","link_text":"William Pantry"},{"type":"founding_family_convergence","related_id":"T00036","display_label":"His son Samuel's marriage brought Pynchon-Holyoke blood into the Talcott line.","link_text":"Capt. Samuel Talcott"},{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"T00038","link_text":"Rev. Jonathan Russell","display_label":"was his grandson, the long-serving Barnstable minister"}],"gender":"male","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Hartford co-founder alongside Thomas Hooker","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Talcott_(Hartford_founder)"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"Co-founder of Hartford, Connecticut alongside Rev. Thomas Ho…","body":"Co-founder of Hartford, Connecticut alongside Rev. Thomas Hooker","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"The only Talcott known to have emigrated","body":"The only Talcott known to have emigrated to America — all American Talcotts descend from him","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Sailed on ship Lyon June 22","body":"Sailed on ship Lyon June 22, 1632 with Hooker's Company, arriving Boston Sept 16, 1632","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Among the 'Adventurers Party' of 25 men who","body":"Among the 'Adventurers Party' of 25 men who explored the Hartford area October 1635, prior to Hooker's party departure May 1636","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Fifth greatest proprietor of houses and lands","body":"Fifth greatest proprietor of houses and lands in Newtown (Cambridge) 1634","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":6,"category":"legacy","header":"His carpenter Nicholas Clark built the first house","body":"His carpenter Nicholas Clark built the first house in Hartford on the ground where the North Church (Dr. Bushnell's) later stood","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":7,"category":"legacy","header":"Was styled 'The Worshipful Mr. John Talcott'","body":"Was styled 'The Worshipful Mr. John Talcott' in colonial records","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":8,"category":"legacy","header":"Mother's daughter Rachel married Hartford Founder John S…","body":"His mother's daughter Rachel married Hartford Founder John Steele; her sister Sarah married Hartford Founder William Wadsworth; he was an uncle of Hartford Founder John Skinner","migrated_from":"historical_significance"}],"bio":{"display_name":"John Talcott","notes":"The only Talcott known to have emigrated to America. Co-founder of Hartford with Rev. Thomas Hooker.","first_name":"John","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781584741/35303680_53fbabf3-2229-47a2-a3a8-d3bec04e7a7b-2_daws5y.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-talcott-1594"},"U00011":{"id":"U00011","visible_default":false,"in_talcott_book":true,"classification":{"is_spouse_of_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1602,"city":"Braintree","county":"Essex","country":"England"},"death":{"year":1670,"month":2,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"T00011","children_ids":["T00034","T00035","T00036"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1660,"date_year":1624}],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","url":"https://archive.org/details/talcottpedigreei00talc"}],"parents":{"has_discrepancy":true,"discrepancy_note":"One source gives parents as 'John Mott and Alice Harington'; Talcott 1876 gives 'Mark Mott and Frances Gutter' with Mark being son of Thomas and Alice (Mead) Mott. The Talcott 1876 reconstruction preferred as more detailed.","mother_research_notes":"Probably Frances Gutter (wife of Mark Mott). Frances died Braintree, buried Feb 23, 1615. Mark Mott died Braintree, buried Dec 14, 1637.","father_research_notes":"Probably Mark Mott, son of Thomas and Alice (Mead) Mott of Braintree, Essex. Talcott 1876 says 'supposed to have been the daughter of Mark, son of Thomas and Alice (Mead) Mott.'"},"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":null,"primary_url":null,"primary_url_label":null},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Dorothy Mott Talcott","first_name":"Dorothy","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":["Talcott"],"maiden_name":"